Step 1 - Familiarize yourself with the data and the assignment

In this assignment you'll build some predictive regression models with R on a dataset containing inpatient discharges from hospitals in New York.

The version of this data that we'll be using is from a Kaggle dataset. See https://www.kaggle.com/jonasalmeida/2015-deidentified-ny-inpatient-discharge-sparcs. Unfortunately, the column metadata wasn't posted. However, since this is a publicly available dataset, we can visit the source at https://health.data.ny.gov/Health/Hospital-Inpatient-Discharges-SPARCS-De-Identified/82xm-y6g8.

If you scroll down on that page you'll find descriptions of the columns (click the little Show All link to display the entire list).

Most of the fields are self-explanatory. You'll notice that there are several sets of diagnosis and procedure codes. A few definitions are helpful.

DRG - Diagnosis Related Groups

DRGs are a coding system developed in the 1980s that form the basis of how hospitals are reimbursed from Medicare (US Govt) or private insurers. After a patient is discharged from the hospital, a program known as a DRG grouper uses information such as diagnosis and procedure codes (ICD-9-CM) to assign a DRG to the patient. A full list of the over 900 DRGs can be found at:

https://www.cms.gov/Research-Statistics-Data-and-Systems/Statistics-Trends-and-Reports/MedicareFeeforSvcPartsAB/downloads/DRGdesc08.pdf

In that list you'll see that MDC (Medical Diagnostic Category) is simply a grouping of DRGs.

CCS - Clinical Classification System

The CCS system was developed by the Agency for Healthcare Research and Quality (AHRQ) to provide a classification system better suited to healthcare research. There are CCS diagnosis codes and CCS procedure codes. From their website:

The Clinical Classifications Software (CCS) for ICD-9-CM is a diagnosis and procedure categorization scheme that can be employed in many types of projects analyzing data on diagnoses and procedures. CCS is based on the International Classification of Diseases, 9th Revision, Clinical Modification (ICD-9-CM), a uniform and standardized coding system. The ICD-9-CM's multitude of codes - over 14,000 diagnosis codes and 3,900 procedure codes - are collapsed into a smaller number of clinically meaningful categories that are sometimes more useful for presenting descriptive statistics than are individual ICD-9-CM codes.

Step 6 - Building and evaluation of predictive models

Now that you know a little more about the data, it's time to start building a few predictive models for Total_Charges. The error metric that we will use to evaluate the models (both for fit and for predictions) is median absolute deviation (MAD). This is nothing more than the median of the absolute value of the residuals for a fitted model.

QUESTION: What might be an advantage of using median absolute deviation instead of mean absolute deviation?

The advantage of using median absolute deviation over mean absolute deviation is that the effect of extreme values is negated. Medians are resistant to outliers, and one or two outliers can dominate a mean. The data set may be relatively consistent but with a few very large/small values. This will result in a larger error metric that will not reflect the relative stability of the data. This is not the case with medians, where the stability would be shown in the error metric.

Obviously we want models with lower MAD values. Our ultimate goal is to create a model that predicts well on the test dataset, ipd_test.

Null model

It's always a good idea to start out with what we call the null model. This is the simplest possible model and one that other models better be able to beat. For this regression problem, the null model is simply a regression model that just has a y-intercept. If you remember some of your statistics, you won't be surprised that the best fit value for the y-intercept in this case is the mean of the response variable, Total_Charges.

charges_lm0 <- lm(Total_Charges ~ 1, data = ipd_train)
summary(charges_lm0)

Model building

Using the information you've gained from reading about the data and doing some EDA, build several regression models and compute the MAD from each. Summarize your results in terms of which model or models appear to fit well.

Identify your top 3 models in terms of lowest MAD values to use in the next part in which you'll use them to make predictions on the test dataset.

# Regression models
charges_lm1 = glm(Total_Charges ~ Length_of_Stay + Health_Service_Area, data = ipd_train)
charges_lm2 = glm(Total_Charges ~ Length_of_Stay + Hospital_County, data = ipd_train)
charges_lm3 = glm(Total_Charges ~ Length_of_Stay * Hospital_County, data = ipd_train)
charges_lm4 = glm(Total_Charges ~ Length_of_Stay : Hospital_County, data = ipd_train)
charges_lm5 = glm(Total_Charges ~ Length_of_Stay : Hospital_County + APR_Risk_of_Mortality + APR_Severity_of_Illness_Desc, data = ipd_train)
charges_lm6 = glm(Total_Charges ~ Length_of_Stay : Hospital_County + APR_Risk_of_Mortality : APR_Severity_of_Illness_Desc, data = ipd_train)

Essentially I started on the assumption that length of stay and location would be correlated to total charges and added on from there. Hospital service area was too broad so hospital county was more significant. Then I tested out the interaction between the two variables. Ultimately I added the severity of illness and risk of mortality to the model and then tested out the interaction between the two, since they would seem to be related. My top 3 models in terms of lowest MAD involve the interaction effects of length of stay and hospital county, with two of them including some form of the risk of mortality and severity of illness. They are: charges_lm4, charges_lm5, and charges_lm6.

Constant variance

Make an appropriate plot to check for constant variance (homeskedasticity) for your top model. Don't remember what kind of plot to make? See my notes on residual analysis or any intro stats book.

ggplot(charges_lm6, aes(x = .fitted, y = .resid)) + geom_point()

The outward funnel shape of the graph shows that the model is heteroskedastic. The assumption of equal variance is not true for all fitted values. The model is more volatile for higher fitted values.

Evaluate the predictions

Compute the MAD for each of the three models' predictions on the test data.

HINT: Obviously you can't use the residuals (or errors) directly but will have to compute them. They are simply the difference between the actual values and your predicted values.

So, for the model I mentioned earlier that had a MAD of 7270.340 for the training data, the MAD on the test data was 7335.559. Notice that MAD for test is higher than MAD for train.

median(abs(ipd_test$Total_Charges - charges_predict_lm4$fit))
## [1] 6827.367
median(abs(ipd_test$Total_Charges - charges_predict_lm5$fit))
## [1] 6504.425
median(abs(ipd_test$Total_Charges - charges_predict_lm6$fit))
## [1] 6466.962

QUESTION: Do you think it's typical that MAD for test would be higher than MAD for train? Why or why not?

It is typical that MAD for test is higher than MAD for train because the model is fitted to the training data, while the model is predicting the test data. It is very easy to build a model that fits a data set, the hard part is making one that predicts new data. The model has never seen the test data and has not been fitted to it, so it would hold that the error metric, in this case MAD, is higher.

QUESTION: Which of your top 3 models had the lowest MAD for the test data?

The model charges_lm6 had the lowest MAD for the test data at 6466.962. This model also had the lowest MAD for the training data at 6366.714.

QUESTION: How do the MAD values for the test data compare to the MAD values for the training data?

The MAD values for all three of the models are higher for the test data than for the train. It is not by a lot, but they are higher. See the below plot for details.

Finally, create some sort of plot which shows the MAD values for both train and test for your top 3 models. One plot.

testMAD <- rbind(median(abs(ipd_test$Total_Charges - charges_predict_lm4$fit)),
median(abs(ipd_test$Total_Charges - charges_predict_lm5$fit)),
median(abs(ipd_test$Total_Charges - charges_predict_lm6$fit)))

trainMAD <- rbind(median(abs(charges_lm4$residuals)),
                  median(abs(charges_lm5$residuals)),
                  median(abs(charges_lm6$residuals)))

lmMAD <- as.data.frame(cbind(trainMAD,testMAD))
names(lmMAD) <- c("Train", "Test")
lmMAD$Model <- sprintf("charges_lm%s", 4:6)
lmMAD_2 <- melt(lmMAD, id.vars = "Model", variable.name = "Data", value.name = "MAD")

lmMAD_2 %>%
  ggplot(aes(Data, MAD)) + geom_point(aes(color = Model)) + labs(title = "Train vs. Test MAD by Model")

My top model is charges_lm6, which includes the interaction between hospital county and length of stay plus the interaction between severity of illness and risk of mortality. I chose these variables based on the exploratory data analysis (EDA) done before model-building. It offered some insight into which variables might matter and which ones might not. Intuitively, length of stay would seem to have an effect on total charges. The longer you are at a hospital, the more money is spent. Certain counties may have different prices for the same services as well, resulting in higher charges for the same illness. I initially chose health service area but it proved too broad, with hospital county being more significant. It is also possible that patients spend more time at hospitals depending on the county, hence why I included the interaction between the two in my model. Demographic information such as gender, race, and age group did not seem to significantly impact the model. For example, the boxplots of charges by gender did not look different enough to suggest a relationship there. Again, it would make sense that the more severe an illness and/or the greater the risk of death, the total charges would be higher as well. This is exactly what the preliminary EDA showed. These two variables are very closely related, which is why I included them as a package. I played with more variables as well but most of them hardly impacted the model at all. I did not want too many variables in the model because it may fit the data well, but it would likely not do so hot predicting new data. I think this model strikes a good balance between simplicity and complexity.
